Smith & Wesson Model 59 9mm Semi-Automatic Pistol

Made in the USA - Springfield, MA

Original owner:  Purchased in 1979.

Fired less than 100 rounds total in lifetime.

Specs:

* Caliber - 9mm Parabellum
* Rate of fire - Semi-automatic
* Weight - 30 oz / 1.84 lb (0.840 kg)
* Length - 7.55 in (192 mm)
* Barrel Length - 4 in (102 mm)
* Cartridge - 9×19mm Parabellum
* Action - Double Action / Single Action
* Feed System - 14-round double column, detachable box magazine
* Sites - fixed Iron sights
* Grips - Black plastic

History:

The Smith & Wesson Model 59 was a modification of the S&W Model 39 pistol that had a double-column magazine. It was one of the first generation of Smith & Wesson semi-automatics.

It was designed for the U.S. Navy as a large-capacity version of the S&W Model 39, the basis of their Mark 22 "Hush Puppy" silenced pistol.  The Model 59 went on the market in 1971.  It went out of production a decade later in 1980.

Design:

The Model 59 was manufactured in 9mm Parabellum caliber with a wider anodized aluminum frame (to accommodate a double-stack magazine), a straight backstrap, a magazine disconnect (the pistol will not fire unless a magazine is in place), and a blued carbon steel slide that carries the manual safety. The grip is of three pieces made of two nylon plastic panels joined by a metal backstrap. It uses a magazine release located to the rear of the trigger guard, similar to the M1911A1.

title: For Sale:  5.56 bolt action rifle
postcontent:
I have a Mossberg MVP 5.56/.223 bolt action rifle for sale. This rifle is brand new, still in the original factory plastic, only removed for pictures. It is unfired and absolutely unused in anyway. I purchased this rifle new from Gander Mountain not very long ago for an upcoming hunting trip. Well, the trip fell through and I really have no need for this rifle. That said, I don't NEED to sell it either so please don't waste my time or yours with low ball type offers. 

Some fun facts about this rifle, most of which is why I end up deciding on this model:

- It can shoot both 5.56 and .223 ammo (unlike most .223 bolt actions that can only shoot .223 ammo). I have several AR's and have a lot of 5.56 ammo accumulated and t's nice to know I can shoot the 5.56 with this rifle as well.
- It has a fully adjustable trigger, as in the owner can adjust it in about 5 minutes without needing any fancy tools or an expensive gunsmith. 
- The barrel is 1:9 twist, meaning is can properly stabilize up to 69 grain ammo. Many .223 bolt action rifles are 1:12 twist meaning they cannot effectively shoot anything higher than 55 grain ammunition. This is important for distance shooting and accuracy.
- This rifle is designed to use standard AR15 magazines. Yup, you read that correctly. any size or form of standard AR15 magazine fits fine (ex. 5/10/20/30 rounders, polymer type like Magpul or metal type like issued by the military...all work in this rifle). No more trying to hunt down specific hard to find magazines, only to pay through the nose.
- Military spec bolt (meaning it is both durable, lightweight, and effective)
- Fluted barrel (20") for reduced weight and heat dissipation. 
- Integral Weaver-style 2-piece bases for such things as optics

Here is a link to the rifle I purchased from the place I bought it from:

Brunton Pocket Transits, typically known as a "BRUNTON", are still considered the most reliable, accurate and most respected field instrument to geologists, surveyors, mining engineers, civil engineers, environmental engineers and foresters worldwide.  This M2: 6050 model utilizes a lightweight composite body and cast NdFeB rare earth magnet needle (similar to the 5008), but features a 0-6400 mils scale instead of a 0-360 degree azimuth scale. Waterproof and accurate to ± 10 mils with a 0-6400 mils ring, the  M2: 6050 model features an induction dampened needle for quick and accurate readings.  And the gear driven magnetic declination adjustment allows for east or west declination settings to 180 degrees.

The vertical angle scale featuring 1 degree increments has a range of ± 90 degrees or 100% grade scale with an accuracy of ± 1/2 degree.  A percent grade scale features increments of 5%.

Other special features include the precision aligned mirror with convenient "see through" sighting capability, short and long sights, composite body material with minimal thermal mass, jeweled bearings, and bubble levels. postcontent:
This is a brand new most recent generation (Gen.3) Zatstava N-Pap AK.  It has 20rds through the barrel to test both mags and dial in the dope.  It's an extremely accurate AK (better than my Arsenal, same as my VEPR, the VEPR gets 2" groups at 100yds with irons on surplus ammo effortlessly).  You should have no problem with easily achieving the same accuracy.  

It has been upgraded tremendously.  It comes with a Midwest Industries AK-SS Extended Handguard with a custom ordered Midwest Industries Yugo upper section, and Troy Industries Vertical Grip.

It has also been coated with KG Industries 2400 Series coatings (this is not the Brownell's junk).  KG 2400 is far more durable than Cerakote and holds up much better to abuse, I have tested it extensively.  I coat firearms professionally and use KG's products on all personal firearms as well as my customer's with dramatically better results over Cerakote.  When we meet I can show you a pre-80's series Colt Combat Commander that has had 540rds through it since it was coated.  The only way you can even tell it's been fired is if you strip it and look at the carbon build up on the inside of the frame.  The coating also makes it extremely easy to clean the rifle, just field strip, and wipe it down.  No need for oil either.  KG 2400 is self lubricating and very convenient.  This AK is rustproof.  The whole rifle has been coated; external barrel, receiver, internal receiver, Tapco G2 trigger, gas tube, piston rod, bolt carrier, top cover, everything.  It sheds water and debris like no other and is extremely smooth.  It's shoots very smoothly as well.     

This whole rifle is top-notch.  Buy with confidence.  It has been thoroughly inspected by me for all the most common AK issues.  It is 110%.  Windage on the front sight is dead center and dead on, only adjustment ever needed is elevation in the rear sight for range.  It is dialed in at 25yds currently.  

It is ready to go for any 1913 pic-rail optics you could ever want to put on it.  

Only one reason I'm even considering selling this rifle:
1.  I have the opportunity to buy three more AK's for the price of one and I gotta do it quick.

title: For Sale:  Ballester - Molina HAFDASA .45acp, Wartime - British Contract.  Similar to both the 1911 and the Star
location: N.E. Side of Janesville, Janesville, Wisconsin
postcontent:
For Sale: Ballester-Molina (Argentine) .45acp manufactured by HAFDASA during WWII - this one is a British Contract pistol, supposedly made for Clandestine purposes!  There is an excellent article in the February 2014 issue of American Rifleman about these pistols, and is worth reading about.  You could also google Ballester-Molina pistols and their History, which is very interesting.  This example is in very nice condition, with wear on the front and rear grip straps.  It has British proofs on the right rear of the slide, and on the right rear of the frame (near the beavertail) plus excellent British proofs on the barrel at the chamber too.  Original blue finish, and it's all matching except the magazine.  All Ballester-Molinas that I have shot have been very accurate!  $875  No taxes, no shipping, no extra fees.  Where else would you find a very nice, British proofed, wartime .45acp?  The really nice and unissued conditioned guns bring around $2K, so this one is a relative bargain.  Thanks for looking
I might consider some late model SIG pistols in trade (p232, M11-a1, p239) or possibly an HK P9s in .45 or a Kimber Solo.

postcontent: .35 Remington Rifle Performance! Lone Eagle / SSP86 Single Shot pistol, chambered in the rare and very effective and very efficient .357 Herrett. 12" barrel, cannon breech. Pretty nice trigger.  INCLUDES SCOPE, RINGS, MOUNTS, RELOADING DIES AND ABOUT 100 CASES!  Includes a Burris 2X pistol scope with target turrets (with the rings and mounts). I bought this new when they first came out. I can't see worth a damn any more, so away it goes. I think it is about the perfect hunting pistol. It's short enough to carry on the forearm of my left arm, and is instantly available to shoot. I normally carried mine uncocked, and cocked just before using it (easy) which was easier than disengaging the safety. It's small enough to slip into your hunting jacket while on a stand or in a snowstorm. I have taken a number of whitetails with mine, and none went anywhere after the 1st shot. The .357 Herrett has .35 Remington Rifle performance in a slightly shorter case. I use the 180 grain pistol bullets and AA1680 powder at about 21-2200fps (not bad out of a 12" barrel). Recoil is manageable, and the pistol is not that heavy. You don't need a big honking flash hider/muzzle brake, which keeps the package smaller, and won't blow out your eardrums quite as fast! I also have RCBS dies and some formed brass that is INCLUDED!! Feel free to ask questions; Thanks for looking. Note: This is a handload only proposition! No factory ammo is available! Note: I forgot to mention that the pistol is easy to handle and to control under recoil due to the balanced location of the grip. The Lone Eagle series are really nice pistols.
